# Package Manager: Yarn Only

## Context
- When working with JavaScript/TypeScript dependencies
- When installing packages
- When modifying package.json
- When creating or updating scripts

## Requirements
- Use Yarn for all package management operations
- Never use npm commands in scripts or documentation
- Use yarn.lock for dependency locking, not package-lock.json
- Use Yarn workspaces for monorepo management if needed
- Document all scripts using Yarn syntax in README and documentation
- Configure CI/CD to use Yarn for building and testing

## Examples
<example>
# Installing dependencies
yarn install

# Adding a package
yarn add react

# Adding a dev dependency
yarn add -D typescript

# Running scripts
yarn dev
yarn build
yarn test
</example>

<example type="invalid">
# Never use npm
npm install
npm run dev
npm i react

# Don't use npx
npx create-react-app my-app
</example>

## Critical Rules
- Always use `yarn` for all package management operations
- Never use `npm` or `npx` commands
- Always use `yarn add` instead of `npm install`
- Never commit package-lock.json to the repository
- Always use `yarn` for running scripts defined in package.json
- Never use global npm installations, prefer `yarn global add` 